{
  "texts": [
    "Classified as Software of Unknown Provenance (SOUP), these systems often do not disclose critical details about their data sources, development methodologies, or validation processes, making it challenging to assess and manage biases that may emerge at various stages of the model lifecycle 8, 20, 21.",
    "While AI systems not designed for medical purposes are not inherently subject to FDA or IRB regulation, concerns arise when these tools are repurposed for patient-facing or clinical decision-making tasks.",
    "Such applications may fall under FDA oversight if the AI is used for diagnosis, treatment, or disease prevention 20.",
    "Although the FDA applies discretionary enforcement policies for lower-risk software, where efficacy evidence may be minimal, the deployment of AI in high-risk contexts-such as interpreting medical data or guiding treatment-without thorough clinical evaluation introduces significant potential risks 19.",
    "Ensuring rigorous, lifecycle-based oversight for AI used in clinical applications is essential to safeguarding patient safety."
  ]
}